###One Shilling
<div style="width:48%;float:left">
<img src="http://localhost/egypt/pietersburg/one-shilling.jpg" style="width:98%;margin-right:10px;display:block"  >
<p style="font-size:smaller">
PIETERSBURG 1901 One Shilling
</p>
</div>


This was the last duty printed. many have calaimed that only one printing took place. Like the 2d
it has an appearance that the cliches were thoroughly cleaned before printing. This is emphasized by the yellow background
of the paper colour.

Mathews astutely notes that the first indication of a second printing came in late 1981.

Although the numbers printed and issued were low, probably due to the then high face value, a fair percentage of the 1 shilling stamps has survived.
Full sheets and large blocks, however, are seldom seen - even unsigned.


###Unsigned Remainders
<hr/>
{{warning: These obviously have no standing as postage stamps, as without the signature they were invalid to be used for postage.
However, in multiples or in sheets their evidence is invaluable for research. As ordered quantities of some duties
must have been exceeded quite considerably notaby for the 2d, 4d and 6d, full advantage may be taken of this rather
unusual opportunity.}}
